    <item>
      <title>Re: Gear Gap Between Raiders and Casuals Too Wide</title>
      <link>http://eqforums.station.sony.com/eq/board/message?board.id=Veterans&amp;message.id=229819#M229819</link>
      <description>&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;This is an honest question.  I don't have an answer.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;What is the lifespan of an expansion?&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Meaning, for how many MORE expansions should it live.  Barring the odd clicky, focus, special item, how long should an expansion last before it's basically a desert.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;To my knowledge, barring the odd exceptional clicky or special drop, Classic, Kunark, Velious and Luclin are now deserted.  PoP still has life due to the unique clickies of PoTime (ergo, flagging to Time to get them) but isn't going strong.  And so on.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Itemization should have the above question in mind.  How long before an expansion is over?&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Meaning, group gear passes the highest end raid gear of that expansion.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;What are we talking about?  Pick a number.  An expansion is dead when it's 4,5,6 expansions behind?  THAT will tell you how to itemize.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;When it's time to forget about PoP, most group items of the latest expansion will be superior to PoP in most ways.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;When it's time to forget about GoD, most group items of the latest expansion will be superior to GoD in most ways.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Personally, I'd be comfortable with anything that's in the 4-6 expansions ago.  Yes I flagged the hard way to get to PoP-Time.  Yes I did my countless Coirnav swarm raids.  But, if the new guys get better 1 group gear than top PoP-Quarm, oh well.  At one point, you have to say &amp;quot;PoP is over.&amp;quot;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Eventually, we'll have to say the same thing about GoD, OoW, DoN, and so on.  Some things will likely keep a mild level of popularity.  Well after the gear blows chunks relatively, people will still be churning out MPG trials for the Resist cap increase.  People will also blow through the whole DoDH Mask quest in the future for that cool mask clicky.  But, overall, GoD and crew will be as dead as Classic, Kunark, and so on, is.  That's part of the game.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;---&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Digression =&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The problem I've faced in discussions with regards to obsolescence of an expansion, is that, some people have actually told me... never.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;It took forever to get a clear answer as to what the big deal with trivialization, mudflation, obsolescence, etc... since the L1 orc pawn is trivial even as an add at L3, even in cloth armour, and is obsolete by L5.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The thing is, that some people have told me that the preservation of solo and group content isn't needed.  Sooner or later, the group of L1s you needed to kill that L5+, won't be needed.  You'll be able to duo it.  Then solo it.  Then pull 2+ at a time.  Most people have no problem with that.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The answer I got (not saying I agree, but the clear answer I got) was that raid mobs were different, special, to be preserved.  As a concept (the game isn't that way, but this is how these people would be happy), that a raid mob would always, ALWAYS need a raid to kill.  If you need 36 old timers to kill a dragon in Classic, that maybe, MAYBE you shave off 1 person per expansion, but that a raid mob can never EVER be taken down by group.  Raid stays raid.  It was designed as a raid, and should stay raid.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Ergo, the best group mob loot of the game, ever, 20+ expansions down the road, shouldn't match the easiest raid level mob of Classic.  One hero, no matter how tough, shouldn't be able to match a dragon.  An army is needed to kill a dragon, period.  And so on.  That's why they are so angry at itemization.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;There is &amp;quot;planned obsolescence&amp;quot; for solo / group mobs. There &amp;quot;shouldn't&amp;quot; be any for raid mobs.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;NOT saying I agree, but that's what some told me, and finally, it's clear, though I don't agree.  You can see the perspective now.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Of course, that means that raiding would be the only way to progress past a certain point, and many people would have objections with that.  However, that's why, when the bar is raised again on loot drops for groups, that people object and go &amp;quot;There goes X amount of raids we'll never do again.&amp;quot;  That's why the progression server is what some people feel ideal.  You HAVE to go through the whole content, as if you were doing it the first time; instead of getting current group / solo / bazaar gear, and skip straight to the last 4 (ish) expansions).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;(I DID say it was a digression)&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;---&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Second digression = It's finally sunk into my head that this is a MMOrpg.  Means that not just time spent, not just how, but WHO you spend it with affects the game immensely.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;In a single person PC game, there is NO DIFFERENCE whatsoever between the person that finishes a 60 hour play time game in...&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;20 weeks of 3 hours / week.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;10 weeks of 6 hours / week.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;3 weeks of 20 hours / week.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;or a glorious &amp;quot;better have lots of coffee&amp;quot; non-stop long week-end marathon of 60 hours.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;In ALL the above cases, the person kills the same mobs, gets the same loots, fights the same final boss mob, and gets the same cheesy &amp;quot;you win&amp;quot; animation at the end.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Not so with MMOrpg / EQ.  The game rewards the MMO part.  You spend 60 hours a month (say) raiding, you'll get more, long run, than 60 hours a month grouping, which is more than 60 hours a month soloing, assuming the very same level of challenge seeking.  The game is designed to MMO- your path, but is &amp;quot;nice&amp;quot; enough to give you the option to solo it if you want.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Kind of like the original Baldur's Gate in reverse.  BG was designed as a solo game.  They added the Multi-Player aspect as an afterthought.  Anyone here ever tried it?  I have.  The entire freaking game pauses if one, ONE person clicks on a merchant.  The entire game ALSO pauses if anyone gets a dialogue.  And so on.  Bloated, clunky, inefficient, and un-fun.  Why?  Because you're doing something the game really wasn't designed to do.  Sure, the designers put multi-player in as an option, but it certainly was an afterthought, or at least, not very well supported, since, at it's core, BG is a solo game.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Ditto here in EQ, though in reverse.  Look at all and I mean ALL the complaints from soloers.  Ever try to solo, and I mean truly solo a Warrior or Rogue.  You can, but good luck.  You need good gear, strategy, choice of zone (pick two), and it's tons harder than grouping or raiding, not that the latter two are &amp;quot;easy&amp;quot; but, quite bluntly, it's not what the game was designed to do.  I wish it was, trust me.  I don't like people and I stay because I love the game engine, but the game was designed to MMO- you.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;---&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;That being said, this is why bazaar gear, vs Solo NODROP gear, vs group NODROP gear, vs raid NODROP gear is totally the subject of the day, any day.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The better the bazaar gear, the more group and raid contents goes obsolete, the faster you get to the end(ish) of the game, the faster you get I've-won-itis, and look for something else to play.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Of course, on the other hand, you can't have the progression path SO frustrating, that the average player quits, and you're left with a tiny player base.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt; &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Those are the balls they have to juggle.  There's a lot I hate about $OE, but in this one aspect, I do feel for their dilemma.  It's a hard, constantly evolving problem.  One of which, will make threads like this, about loot, not just popular, but the topic of the day, any day, till the end of the game...&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Message Edited by Quadd_Luclin on &lt;span class="date_text"&gt;05-18-2006&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="time_text"&gt;11:38 PM&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
